# Line-ending policy for sdk-unity.
#
# NOTE: .gitattributes do not cross repository boundaries, so this submodule does
# not inherit the workspace-root .gitattributes. It needs its own.
#
# Git for Windows ships core.autocrlf=true as a SYSTEM default
# (C:/Program Files/Git/etc/gitconfig). It makes Git check text files out as CRLF
# and cache the CRLF-expanded size in the index stat cache. Tooling that rewrites a
# file with LF then produces a smaller real size, and Git reports it modified from
# the stat cache alone — without hashing the content. `git diff` is empty, and
# `git update-index --really-refresh` refuses to correct it. The file is permanently
# phantom-dirty.
#
# The Unity Editor is exactly that kind of tooling: it serializes .unity / .asset /
# .meta / .asmdef YAML with LF on every save, regardless of platform. This repo is
# consumed as a Git UPM package, so a fresh clone on any consumer's Windows machine
# is the normal case, not an edge case.
#
# `build.gradle` is consumed by Unity's Android Gradle build (which runs it through
# a JVM on any host), and `export-unitypackage.ps1` is PowerShell, conventionally
# CRLF on Windows and safest pinned that way.
#
# Deliberately targeted at the Unity-serialized asset types rather than a blanket
# `* text=auto eol=lf`, which would rewrite the whole working tree on next checkout.
*.unity   text eol=lf
*.asset   text eol=lf
*.meta    text eol=lf
*.asmdef  text eol=lf
*.prefab  text eol=lf
*.mat     text eol=lf
*.anim    text eol=lf
*.controller text eol=lf
*.gradle  text eol=lf
*.ps1     text eol=crlf
